The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A Citu convention at Yuva Bharati Krirangan, in Salt Lake, disrupted traffic for over two hours at the Ultadanga-VIP Road crossing on Sunday afternoon. Airport-bound commuters, among others, had a trying time because of the snarl.

 mong those who addressed the gathering were Jyoti Basu, chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee and senior Citu leaders. Thousands of Citu supporters from far-flung areas, waving red flags, came in a string of processions, choking all approaches to VIP Road. Trucks and private buses carrying the rallyists were parked on the roads.

 Several suburban trains in the Eastern Railway?s Sealdah and Howrah divisions stand cancelled on Tuesday on the occasion of Holi. Railway officials said 74 local trains in the Sealdah division and 58 in the Howrah division have been cancelled. Some trains in Sealdah division will be terminated short of their destinations. 

 The Howrah-New Delhi Poorva Express will leave at 6.45 pm on Monday, instead of its scheduled departure time of 9.10 am, officials said. Late arrival of the corresponding Down train has resulted in the delay. Some long-distance trains from Calcutta were running late as a passenger train was derailed at Mughalsarai on Friday night. 

 A workshop on cardiac problems and pacemaker therapy was held at RG Kar Medical College and Hospital. The workshop highlighted the various aspects of pacemaker therapy. Similar programmes will soon be held at other hospitals, state-run and private.

 A diabetes fair was organised at Apollo Gleneagles Hospitals on Sunday. A host of endocrinologists, diabetologists, cardiologists, orthopaedic surgeons, nephrologists, ophthalmologists and gynaecologists took part in panel discussions. Interactive sessions were held with patients and their family members. 

 A section of state government employees has demanded an increase in the insurance coverage during election duty. A resolution to the effect was adopted at the 8th annual conference of the State Government Employees? Federation in Salt Lake. Federation general secretary P.B. Nag said the insurance coverage should be raised from Rs 2 lakh to Rs 5 lakh for state government employees sent on election duty.

 Police on Sunday brought 64 Bangladeshis, who had illegally entered the country, to Barrackpore. They will be handed over to the BSF. 

 The parks and gardens wing of the civic body will soon talk to the mayor to decide what is to be done with pavement trees that are damaging the foundations of buildings. ?We will also discuss the issue with the forest department,? said Faiyaz Khan, mayoral council member (parks and gardens).

